{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595935"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:08:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:08:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15382"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15382"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.88,0.03,0,0.09,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8073"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68557"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8073"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15382"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54014"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6929"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8552"},{"type":"tags","id":"8666"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19594"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19599"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68557"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-week-old infant presents with delayed passage of meconium, abdominal distension, and vomiting. Rectal biopsy is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the underlying pathophysiology of Hirschsprung disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Failure of neural crest cell migration to bowel wall","Degeneration of existing ganglion cells","Excessive proliferation of enteric neurones","Primary smooth muscle dysfunction","Inflammatory destruction of ganglion cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHirschsprung disease is caused by \u003Cstrong\u003Efailure of neural crest cell migration to bowel wall\u003C/strong\u003E during embryonic development. This results in an aganglionic segment that lacks both submucosal (Meissner\u0027s) and myenteric (Auerbach\u0027s) plexuses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDegeneration of existing ganglion cells\u003C/strong\u003E - The ganglion cells never develop in the affected segment rather than degenerating\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive proliferation of enteric neurones\u003C/strong\u003E - The condition is characterised by absence, not excess, of enteric neurones\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary smooth muscle dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E - The smooth muscle dysfunction is secondary to absence of ganglion cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory destruction of ganglion cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a developmental disorder, not an inflammatory condition\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe aganglionic segment is unable to relax, leading to a functional obstruction. The condition typically begins at the internal anal sphincter and extends proximally for varying distances.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hirschsprung disease results from failed migration of neural crest cells during embryonic development, leading to absence of ganglion cells in the bowel wall","The condition typically affects the rectum and sigmoid colon, progressing proximally in varying lengths","Absence of ganglion cells leads to persistent contraction of the affected segment, causing functional obstruction"],"references":["Sergi C. Hirschsprung\u0027s disease: Historical notes and pathological diagnosis on the occasion of the 100(th) anniversary of Dr. Harald Hirschsprung\u0027s death. World J Clin Pediatr. 2015 Nov 8;4(4):120-5. doi: 10.5409/wjcp.v4.i4.120. PMID: 26566484; PMCID: PMC4637802.","Lotfollahzadeh S, Taherian M, Anand S. Hirschsprung Disease. 2023 Jun 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32965813.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54014"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15382"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54014"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T20:33:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T20:34:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8073"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68557"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"met